Quantum Supremacy Demonstration by Employing a Pulse-Based Variational Quantum Algorithm to Tackle a Large Optimization Problem - Draft 4

Ohad Lev

May-June 2024

In this notebook we focus on a single issue: the QEMC algorithm's cost function and its behaviour when we vary $B$ - the number of expected "blue" nodes in the graph.

The QEMC algorithm's cost function:

$$ \mathcal{L}_1(G) = \sum_{(i, j) \in E} \bigg(p_i + p_j - \frac{1}{B} \bigg)^2 + \bigg(|p_i - p_j| - \frac{1}{B} \bigg)^2 \tag{1} $$

Where:

  • $E$ is the set of edges in the graph $G = (V, E)$.
  • $p_i$, $p_j$ are the probabilities associated with the nodes $i$, $j$.
  • $B$ is the number of "blue" nodes in the graph.

1. What's not working?

When $B \approx 1/2$, it seems that everything works fine. But when we force $B << |V|$, it seems that the algorithm doesn't work, as seen clearly in this plot we generated in January 2024:

The above results can be explained due to two main reasons:

  1. When $B << |V|$, $1/B$ is large and the classification threshold $1 / 2B$ is also large. So even if the algorithm manages to drive probabilities in the right direction, it is very hard for a probability to cross the classification threshold, hence we see QEMC cuts that are zero or very close to zero.

  2. The problem above doesn't seem so fatalic if the algorithm still does its job during the optimization process (i.e, it drives probabilities in the right directions), because we can choose the $B$ most large probabilities and classify their corresponding nodes as "blue". But is it the case that the algorithm does its job in the regime of $B << |V|$? In the above plot it seems that there is some convergence of the cost function in every plot, which is a good sign, but we need to check.

2. Analyzing the behaviour of the QEMC cost function in the $B << |V|$ regime

Consider the $3$-regular problem instance where $|V| = 64$, $|E| = 96$ and $B = 4$.

In the ideal case (we assume the ideal case is possible in this problem setting, it's a plausible assumption) where all the $B = 4$ probabilities associated with the "blue" nodes equal $1/B = 1/4$, and the rest of the probabilites are $0$, the cost function is:

$$ \mathcal{L}_{\text{ideal}} = (|E| - 3B) \cdot \frac{2}{B^2} = (96 - 12) \cdot \frac{2}{16} = \frac{84}{8} = 10.5 \tag{2} $$

In the trivial, random noise, uniform distribution case, the cost function is:

$$ \mathcal{L}_{\text{uniform}} = |E| \cdot \Bigg[ \bigg( \frac{2}{|V|} - \frac{1}{B} \bigg)^2 + \frac{1}{B^2} \Bigg] = 96 \cdot \Bigg[ \bigg( \frac{2}{64} - \frac{1}{4} \bigg)^2 + \frac{1}{16} \Bigg]= 96 \cdot \bigg( \frac{7^2}{32^2} + \frac{1}{16} \bigg) = 10.59375 \tag{3} $$

So we see that the trivial uniform distribution is almost as "good" as the ideal distribution - it's a problem.

We check also numerically:

In[1]:
import networkx as nx
from draft_4_util_funs import (
    qemc_cost_fun,
    obtain_uniform_distribution,
    obtain_pseudo_ideal_distribution
)

B = 4

uniform_distribution = obtain_uniform_distribution(num_nodes)
pseudo_ideal_distribution = obtain_pseudo_ideal_distribution(num_nodes, B)

cost_value_uniform_distribution = qemc_cost_fun(graph, uniform_distribution, B)
cost_value_pseudo_ideal_distribution = qemc_cost_fun(graph, pseudo_ideal_distribution, B)

print("L_ideal =", cost_value_pseudo_ideal_distribution)
print("L_uniform =", cost_value_uniform_distribution)

L_ideal = 10.75
L_uniform = 10.59375

Either way, I think that it can be intersting to numerically test the QEMC algorithm when $B << |V|$, but when in the end of the process the blue nodes are chosen as those that corresponds with the largest probabilities.

3. Regularization and penalization of the QEMC cost function

It can make sense to integrate modifications for the cost function in order to make uniform distribution case undesireable and the unique solution distribution case desireable. Hence, consider the following additional notations:

  • $\mathcal{P}$ - the probability distribution generated by measuring the QEMC circuit multiple times.
  • $\mathcal{U}$ - the uniform probability distribution over the same sample space as $\mathcal{P}$.
  • $\mathrm{Var[\mathcal{X}]}$ - variance of a (discrete) probability distribution $\mathcal{X}$.
  • $\lambda$ - regularization hyperparameter.
  • $\mathrm{Distance \big (\mathcal{X}_1, \mathcal{X}_2 \big)}$ - some distance function between two probability distributions over the same sample space - I have thought of employing the KL divergence, but it turned out to be a bad idea because it blows to inifinity in cases where in one distribution there exist a nonzero probability for a state with zero probability in the other. Maybe the Wasserstein metric is what we are looking for, but I need to look at it. TBD.

And consider the following modified cost functions:

$$ \mathcal{L}_2 = \mathcal{L}_1 \cdot \big(-\mathrm{Var}[\mathcal{P}] \big) \tag{4} $$

$$ \mathcal{L}_3 = \mathcal{L}_1 - \lambda\mathrm{Var}[\mathcal{P}] \tag{5} $$

$$ \mathcal{L}_4 = \mathcal{L}_1 \cdot \bigg[ \mathrm{-Distance} \big(\mathcal{P}, \mathcal{U} \big) \bigg] \tag{6} $$

$$ \mathcal{L}_5 = \mathcal{L}_1 - \lambda \cdot \mathrm{Distance} \big(\mathcal{P}, \mathcal{U} \big) \tag{7} $$

4. Methodology definition for QEMC simulations to obtain the best cost function

The next phase, in my opinion, is calculating and\or simulating all combinations of the following settings:

  • $|V| \in \{16, 32, 64, 128 \}$.
  • $B \in \{2, 4, 8, 16, 32, 64 \}$ (while obviously not surpassing $B = |V| / 2$ for a given graph).
  • The cost function $\mathcal{L} \in \{\mathcal{L}_1, \mathcal{L}_2, \mathcal{L}_3, \mathcal{L}_4, \mathcal{L}_5 \}$.
  • Coloring only nodes associated with probabilities that crossed the classification threshold VS coloring the $B$ nodes associated with the $B$ largest probabilities.

For the small instances, we can also compare our results to those obtained by brute force. For the large instances, it won't work, e.g. ${{128}\choose{64}} \approx 2.4 \times 10^{37}$.

We can use the Burer rank-two relaxation algorithm to obtain fast high-quality cuts for the large instances - I do not know, however, how to perform this for a specific number of "blue" nodes (if possible). TBD.
